LLMs are not intuitive. A+B always equals C. There is no other possible answer. LLMs are probabilistic. If you are living in the average LLMs will work very well for you. If you are odd, weird, and otherwise unusual they will have a reduced efficacy. However, LLMs are often better at brute force. I could not remember what 5000 programmers wrote in the last year but if the LLM has access then it can. As long as we keep building computers and linking them together it will never have a problem like "my brain is full" (as in a 1986 Far Side cartoon). So what a human might consider an unusual request might be common within the population of 5000 programmers.


